<!--
Austrian German (de-AT) translation вАФ full UI coverage. Du-form
throughout, intimate / spousal register matching the existing insight
prose. No Sie-form anywhere. Brand name "ClothesCast" stays verbatim.

Austrian Standard German for formal app UI is, for the most part,
identical in writing to German Standard German вАФ the well-known
Austrianisms (J√§nner / Feber, Marille, Erd√§pfel, Faschiertes,
Sackerl, вА¶) are food / month / household terms that don't appear in a
weather-and-clothes app's UI. Where Austrian register naturally
diverges in *this* app's strings we adjust:

- "Handy-Sprache" (AT) for what de-DE renders as "Telefonsprache" вАФ
  "Handy" is the unmarked Austrian term for a mobile phone in formal
  writing; "Telefon" reads as the landline.
- "kurze Hose" / "lange Hose" stay as in de-DE; AT speakers also use
  these for the garment labels and the Today screen's outfit chips.
- "√Я" stays вАФ Austria writes √Я like Germany. (Swiss German is the
  one that drops it; see values-de-rCH.)

The rest is byte-identical to values-de вАФ duplicated rather than
inherited so a translator opening this file sees the full Austrian
copy in one place instead of having to walk a fallback chain.

What is NOT overridden, by design:
- `app_name` вАФ brand identifier, identical across locales.
- `insight_time_am` / `_pm` / `_midnight` / `_noon` (and the *_minutes
  variants) вАФ English-only spoken-time formatter helpers. German
  locales use `insight_time_hour` / `insight_time_hour_minutes`
  ("15 Uhr" / "15 Uhr 30") which are translated below; the AM/PM keys
  exist for `Locale.language == "en"` paths only and would never be
  read in a German runtime.

Picker labels under `settings_region_language_*` and
`settings_tts_voice_locale_*` give the German names for every offered
locale (Englisch (Vereinigte Staaten), Franz√ґsisch (Kanada), Chinesisch
(vereinfacht), вА¶). The locale tag stored on disk (en-US / fr-CA /
zh-CN) is unchanged; only the displayed label localizes.
-->
